An '''Inertial foot pod''' is a device used to track running measurements such as [[speed]], [[distance]] travelled, [[pace (speed)|pace]], etc., which would generally only be available on [[treadmill]]s or with a [[GPS]] unit.<ref>{{cite book|title=Runner's Edge, The|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=9781450409025|page=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dcWybPNh6GwC&pg=PA22&dq=foot+pod&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjryaaf4ZTYAhXq5oMKHSrgD48Q6AEIODAD#v=onepage&q=foot%20pod&f=false|language=en}}</ref>

This device is usually small and attaches to a runner's foot.  It uses one or more [[accelerometer]]s and processes several times a second to compute speed.

One example is the foot pod employed by the [[Polar S625x]] running computer.

